In the context of genes working together in specific networks to carry out different functions, variations in these genes can change their roles and affect disease-relevant biological processes. Understanding how genes influence complex traits requires examining gene expression regulation across various cell types, which should ultimately lead to improved treatments. Previous studies have described different regulatory DNA elements, including genetic effects on gene expression across diverse tissues. Integrating functional genomics data and GWAS data has enhanced the identification of transcriptional mechanisms that, when dysregulated, often result in tissue- and cell lineage-specific pathology.

In this study, we aim to address a knowledge gap by investigating the role of specific regulatory DNA elements in gene expression across various tissues and cell types. By integrating functional genomics data with GWAS data, we seek to improve our understanding of the transcriptional mechanisms underlying tissue- and cell lineage-specific pathology. This research has the potential to advance our knowledge of complex traits and contribute to the development of novel treatments for diseases affected by these mechanisms.

In summary, this manuscript focuses on the role of specific regulatory DNA elements in gene expression across various tissues and cell types. By integrating functional genomics data with GWAS data, we aim to enhance our understanding of the transcriptional mechanisms underlying tissue- and cell lineage-specific pathology, ultimately contributing to the development of improved treatments for diseases affected by these mechanisms.

Transcription-wide association studies (TWAS) are an effective approach to achieve this by integrating expression quantitative trait loci (eQTLs) data, providing a mechanistic interpretation of GWAS findings [@doi:10.1371/journal.pgen.1009482; @doi:10.1038/ng.3506; @doi:10.1371/journal.pgen.1007889; @doi:10.1038/ng.3367]. TWAS examines whether perturbations in gene regulatory mechanisms link genetic variants to human diseases, and this method has been highly successful in understanding disease etiology at the transcriptome level [@pmid:33931583; @doi:10.1101/2021.10.21.21265225; @pmid:31036433] and in tasks such as disease-risk prediction (polygenic scores) [@doi:10.1186/s13059-021-02591-w] and drug repurposing [@doi:10.1038/nn.4618]. However, TWAS operates at the individual gene level, which doesn't capture the more complex interactions at the network level.

In this study, we aim to address this gap by exploring gene co-expression patterns and their associations with genetic factors, shedding light on disease etiology and drug mechanisms through a comprehensive analysis of functional genomics data. Our approach not only enhances our understanding of therapeutic targets but also contributes to the field of drug repurposing and clustering of complex traits, ultimately providing valuable insights for future research and clinical applications.<|end_of_turn|>

Given the wealth of gene expression data available across multiple tissues, an effective approach to identifying biological processes is through transcription-wide association studies (TWAS) [@doi:10.1038/nbt.3838; @doi:10.1038/s41467-018-03751-6; @doi:10.1126/science.aaz1776; @doi:10.1186/s13040-020-00216-9]. Despite their successes, TWAS does not fully capture the complexity of gene interactions at the network level, leaving room for further exploration and understanding.<|end_of_turn|>

Gene expression data across multiple tissues offers a valuable opportunity to identify biological processes related to diseases. However, current methods like the transcription-wide association study (TWAS) only focus on individual genes and don't capture complex interactions at the network level. TWAS integrates gene regulatory mechanisms with genetic variant data to understand disease etiology at the transcriptome level [@pmid:33931583; @doi:10.1101/2021.10.21.21265225; @pmid:31036433]. While TWAS has been successful in disease-risk prediction (polygenic scores) [@doi:10.1186/s13059-021-02591-w] and drug repurposing tasks [@doi:10.1038/nn.4618], it doesn't fully capture the complex interactions at the network level. This study aims to address this knowledge gap by exploring gene co-expression patterns in disease etiology and drug mechanisms, potentially leading to new therapeutic targets and improved understanding of clustering of complex traits.<|end_of_turn|>
